- Current Clinical Status: Suspected slightly progressive hepatic metastases under ongoing therapy
- Question for Tumor Board: Further therapy?

### Guideline Evidence

#### ESMO 2020 Gastroenteropancreatic neuroendocrine neoplasms
- Is Relevant: True
- Reason: The patient has a small intestine neuroendocrine tumor (SI-NET), specifically in the distal ileum, which is within the scope of this guideline. The tumor is well-differentiated (NET G1) and has metastasized to the liver. The guideline covers diagnosis, treatment, and follow-up for GEP-NENs, including SI-NETs, and mentions specific management strategies for metastatic well-differentiated NETs.
- Relevant Sections:
  - Treatment for non-functioning tumors: Somatostatin analogues (SSAs) are standard first-line therapy. Locoregional therapies (like TACE, NSW, RFA, or ablative techniques) can be considered as an alternative to systemic therapies in patients with liver-limited or predominant disease [IV, B].
  - Surgery for metastatic disease: A surgical approach is indicated in selected patients affected by stage IV GEP-NETs who have exclusive or predominant liver involvement, after careful evaluation of tumour grading, distribution of LMs and primary site [IV, B].
  - Antiproliferative therapy: Everolimus is EMA-approved for progressive Pan-NET G1/G2 with or without prior ChT, for NF-GI and lung NETs [I, A]. In GI NETs, everolimus should be used in patients with clearly progressive disease [I, A]. Sunitinib is EMA approved for advanced progressive Pan-NETs [I, A].
  - Systemic chemotherapy: Systemic ChT is recommended in Pan-NETs and in NEN G3 of any site [II, A]. For non-pancreatic well-differentiated G1/G2 GI NETs, ChT cannot be recommended [II, C].
  - PRRT: PRRT is recommended in patients with midgut NETs with disease progression on SSAs who fulfil the general requirements for PRRT [I, A]. PRRT may be considered in pancreatic NETs after failure of approved therapies [III, A]. PRRT may also be considered in NET G3 [IV, C].
  - Follow-up: Imaging is recommended every 3–6 months for patients with R0/R1-resected NET G1/G2, and every 2–3 months for NEC G3 [V, C].
  - Adjuvant therapy: Adjuvant therapy is not indicated in NET G1/G2 [IV, A].
  - Surgery may also play a role in metastatic disease, especially in selected patients with exclusive or predominant liver involvement [IV, B].
  - In patients with NF-Pan-NETs ≤2 cm, a conservative approach with surveillance consisting of yearly high-quality imaging is suggested [IV, B].
  - For NF-Pan-NETs >2 cm, standard pancreatectomy with regional lymphadenectomy is recommended [IV, A].
  - Macroscopic radical resection of localised SI-NETs is recommended along with systematic mesenteric lymphadenectomy [IV, A]. Palliative resection of primary SI-NETs is generally indicated for preventing complications related to bowel obstruction or intestinal ischemia [IV, C].

### Trial Evidence

